module IfPredUnsafe

(* The mutant of 26_ifpred_safe.lark.  `abs` and its guarded postcondition are
   UNCHANGED and still honest — the lie is at the call.  `main` divides by `abs(0)`.

   The postcondition's guard instantiates at `x = 0`: `0 >= 0` is TRUE, so the THEN
   disjunct fires and the caller learns `a == 0` (and `a >= 0`).  The division
   `100 / a` then owes `a != 0`, which is FALSE, so it goes UNPROVED — exactly one of
   the three obligations.  abs's own two body obligations still prove.

   This is the mutant a broken `if`-translation would wave through: if the else
   branch collapsed to `true`, or the guard were dropped, the checker could conclude
   `a != 0` from the wrong disjunct.  It does not — the guard at `x = 0` selects the
   then-disjunct and `a == 0` stands.

   Were the division admitted, it would divide 100 by 0 at run time. *)

fn abs(x : Int) : {v : Int | v >= 0 and (if x >= 0 then v == x else v == 0 - x)} =
  if x >= 0 then x else 0 - x

fn main(io : IO) : IO =
  let a = abs(0) in
  print(io, show(100 / a))
